{
  "doc_id": "50115",
  "text": "There is evidence that the likelihood of having a road accident in the early morning is related to the commute home after a night shift [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Additionally, in a study of medical interns in the US, the risk of a traffic accident was significantly increased when travelling home from work after an extended shift as compared to a shift of normal duration (Barger et al, 2005) . [CITATION_4] examined trafficrelated incidents in nurses commuting to and from their shifts and found that in both permanent and rotating nightshift nurses, sleepiness and driving events during their commutes were more RAIL WORKER ACCIDENT RISK FACTORS common after their night shifts than before them. \"Shift workers were over eight times more likely to experience hazardous driving events [… ] during commutes home following an 8-10-h shift, compared with during their drive to work.\" (Ftouni et al, 2013, p.64) .",
